data.content:
Yes! MSTest 3.7+ supports **ValueTuple-based `DynamicData`**, eliminating the `object[]` casts:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- Return type: `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)>`
- Data entries: `["value", true]` → `("value", true)`

This gives you compile-time type checking — if you accidentally swap argument types or add a wrong-typed value, you'll get a compiler error instead of a runtime cast failure.
